Crawford County has established a COVID-19 information phone line for residents who do not have access to the internet or subscribe to local media. Unemployment Compensation
https://www.uc.pa.gov/Pages/default.aspx
People may be eligible if:
Their employer temporarily closes or goes out of business because of COVID-19
Their employer reduces your hours because of COVID-19
They have been told not to work because employer feels they might get or spread COVID-19
They have been told to quarantine or self-isolate, or live/work in a county under government-recommended mitigation efforts.
There are four ways they can file a claim:
Online: Complete an online application using their secure website 24/7
https://www.paclaims.pa.gov/UCEN/Welcome.asp
Paper: A paper application can be downloaded and mailed to the address indicated on the form.
https://www.uc.pa.gov/Documents/UC_Forms/UC-42(I).pdf
Videophone: Services for individuals who use American Sign Language (ASL) can be reached at 717-704-8474 every Wednesday from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Phone: Call the statewide toll-free number at 1-888-313-7284.
They will need the following information before they start: SSN/Home address and mailing address (if different)/Telephone number/Valid email/PIN - Personal Identification Number (optional) If they have previously filed a UC claim using a previous PIN they can use that to prevent them from having to re-enter information/Direct deposit bank information (optional) - bank name, address, account and routing number.

Crawford County Mental Health Awareness Programs (CHAPS)
https://chapsinc.org/
Call: (814) 333-2924
Text: (814) 807-9360
CHAPS buildings are closed; however, staff are still working and available to provide assistance.
CHAPS is still taking referrals for all programs. Housing advocates are also continuing to connect individuals in need to permanent housing, shelters and safe spaces. 
Utility assistance program (CSS) is also still available for those with a shutoff notice for gas or electric service. Please call us between 8:00 AM and 4:30 PM for more information.
Grab and Go free lunches are distributed 7 days a week from 12:00 PM to 1:00 PM outside at CHAPS parking lot, at 944 Liberty Street. Individuals are welcome to seek assistance with staff during this time as well. Lunches are also delivered to consumers during weekdays if necessary.
Current consumers will receive regular phone calls to make sure their basic needs are met, including having sufficient groceries, necessary medications, and to check-in on their mental and physical well-being.
Staff will drop off groceries and medications as needed to those needing this assistance. 
Those receiving rep payee assistance still have their support. Spending money will be given, and bills will continue to be paid. Please feel free to call or text your rep payee for any questions:
Crystal Humes, Call: (814) 373-5073 or Text: (814) 813-1247
Lizzie Rhodes, Call: (814) 373-5072 or Text: (814) 273-9110
Please call CHAPS Warmline for non-emergency peer support. The phone is answered 7 days a week from 5:00 PM to 8:00 PM. All calls are confidential. Call: (814) 724-5161.
Our Family Outreach and Family and Peer Support groups continue to operate through a phone support network. If you would like to be part of this network, call CHAPS at 333- 2924, and ask for Sally Burns.

Virtual Counseling is available at Mercy House for those not able to leave their homes or those who request it. They can perform drug and alcohol assessments, individual or couples and family counseling. All you need is a computer or android device. When you make an appointment you will receive a notice to enter the virtual waiting room and they will start the video chat (HIPPA compliant). This is for established as well as new clients who are struggling in response to isolation and fear. Also remember -- this too shall pass, but in the meantime we are here to help you get through it. Call the number above for an appointment or for more details on how to get started.

Peace4Crawford Hope Line
http://peace4crawford.org/
814-724-1116
833-491-HOPE (4673) (toll free)
Crawford County’s trauma informed initiative, Peace4Crawford launched this county-wide telephone “warm line” to assist local residents and families throughout the duration of the current COVID-19/Coronavirus crisis. People in need of assistance may call the Hope Line from 9am to 9pm seven days a week. Calls will be triaged by Women’s Services Hotline staff and referred to one of a group of over 40 trained local volunteers willing to help individuals work through non-emergency challenges as a result of the spread and impact of COVID-19. The Hope Line is not for emergencies. However, the Hope Line may help alleviate some of the additional burden expected on local emergency lines and first responders, keeping those open for true emergencies. The Hope Line also adds another point of contact to help people identify and access local services and accurate information to keep themselves and their families safe during this difficult time.

Only patients who have been previously evaluated by an AHN-affiliated health care provider for COVID-19 symptoms and who have a valid prescription order from their clinicians may be tested at the drive-up collection sites at this time. On-demand or walk-up testing is not available at these locations.
 
To obtain a test order, the network is encouraging patients – especially those with COVID-19 or flu-like symptoms, such as fever, cough, and shortness of breath – to utilize AHN’s various online or phone hotline options, in order to minimize exposure to others.
 
Patients can call the AHN 24/7 Nurse phone line (412-Nurse4U) to discuss symptoms with a nurse, or schedule a video visit or an e-visit through MyChart to discuss their concerns with a clinician. After the COVID-19 test is ordered, patients will be contacted directly by AHN to set up a collection appointment.

Corry Middle/High School
https://sites.google.com/a/corrysd.net/casd/home
534 E. Pleasant Street in Corry
Meal order and pick up process 
Preorder is REQUIRED each day 
Dial 814-664-4677 enter #1 for the District Administration Office 
State student’s first and last name (only 1 name necessary per household) 
State quantity of meals needed (all children in your household age 1 - 18 are eligible for free meals even if they do not attend CASD) 
You must call between the hours of 8AM-4PM the day prior to meal service 
Remember to call on Wednesday and Friday 
Place order on: Wednesday for Thursday pickup (meals for Thursday, Friday) Friday for Monday pickup (meals for Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday) 
Additional meals available for students that drop in, but availability will be limited 
Pick up will be curbside drive through (you do not need to get out of your vehicle) 
Please line up in a single lane against the curb. 
Location is the middle/high school front entrance door 
Pick up time 11am – 1pm Monday and Thursday 
Breakfast and Lunch for each day is provided 

Sheetz
https://www.sheetz.com/news/kidzmeals
Kidz Meal Bagz is a program providing free meals to help children and families in need as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Meals will be available all day starting Thursday, April 2nd and will include a turkey sandwich, chips and a drink. Families interested in taking advantage of the free Kidz Meal Bagz program should go to participating Sheetz locations and ask an employee at the register for a meal. Families will be offered one bag per child. Meals will be available daily while supplies last.

Food Pantries/Other Free Food Programs
Calvary Baptist Church, Charis Cupboard
543 Randolph Street in Meadville
First Saturday of the Month
All City of Meadville residents are eligible for toiletries and household cleaning items. Just bring proof of city residence. Not based on income, residence only.

Center for Family Services
http://www.ctrforfamilyservices.org/
If you have been impacted by #COVID19 and have never been to the food pantry, you should call first so they can get your information over the phone and minimize in-person contact. You can call them at 814.337.8454. Leave a message with your name, address, and phone number.

Households must utilize the food pantry designated for their zip code area, unless an arrangement is made with a CFS staff member. The Center Food Pantries provide one supplemental food box per month per household. Supplemental Food box eligibility is determined on a self declaration of need based on the current 150% of Poverty guidelines but no one is turned away. Additional Emergency Food Boxes are distributed on a case by case basis.

Aging and Disability Resource Centers (ADRC) are a nationwide effort to take a seamless approach in the way we assist seniors and adults with disabilities who need help with activities of daily living. The ADRC in Pennsylvania is known as the Link. How can the Link assist you and/or your family?
•Easily connect you to local services/supports through any Link partner agency
•Explore existing options to ensure a secure plan for independence
•Assist consumers with applications to determine funding eligibility
•Help consumers remain or return to their community because of a disability, an illness or accident, or to transition from an institution back to the community. There is no charge for information and assistance provided by any Link or Link partner agency.

LIFE-NWPA
http://lifenwpa.org/
LIFE-NWPA continues to provide services to seniors during COVID-19, with the exception of adult day services, which have been closed by the State of PA. They are also still enrolling seniors and are doing so safely with the necessary precautions in place. LIFE-NWPA provides the following services: 

Medical Transportation
In-Home Care
Home Delivered Meals

Occupational Therapy
Skilled Care 
On-Call Services
Primary Care

Hospitalization
Emergency Care
Medications

Nutrition Services
